+# Decision Memo - exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit / decision-005
+
+## Decision
+
+`proceed`
+
+## Mission-Control Verdict
+
+`step-002` now passes the active chain's second gate. The present record does
+not stop at the earlier launcher/runtime failures. `RESULTS.md`,
+`state.json`, and the exploration reports now contain the missing Chain Step 2
+mathematical deliverables:
+
+- a bounded three-candidate family:
+  `Template-Defect Near-Closure`,
+  `Windowed Spectator-Leakage Budget`,
+  `Delayed-Threshold Itinerary`;
+- one shared exact five-channel interaction core plus named forced spectator
+  classes;
+- one downstream gate per candidate; and
+- an explicit verdict that Chain Step 3 is well-posed.
+
+That is enough to keep the current branch alive. The unresolved question after
+`step-002` is no longer whether the mission has a concrete object set. It is
+whether those three objects survive the robustness discipline already built
+into the winning chain:
+true exact symmetries,
+frozen canonicalization choices,
+and substantive modeling changes.
+That is exactly the next logical chain step, so mission control should proceed
+to `step-003`.
+
+The operational defects recorded in the step reasoning remain part of the
+provenance, but they no longer justify branch stop or branch comparison. The
+step package now contains decision-grade mathematical outputs, and mission
+control should judge the branch by those outputs.
+
+## Why `replan` Is Wrong
+
+Replanning is for branch weakness, branch closure, or a newly superior branch.
+`step-002` shows the opposite. It sharpens the branch by reducing the object
+family to three explicit candidates with exact interaction templates and named
+gates. None of the Step-2 kill conditions fired, and the step verdict is
+explicitly that Chain Step 3 is well-posed. Opening a fresh branch comparison
+now would discard the first concrete object set the mission has earned before
+testing whether it is robust.
+
+## Why `terminate` Is Wrong
+
+The mission has not reached a terminal positive obstruction, a terminal
+negative kill, or a definition-level collapse. `step-002` did not complete the
+chain; it prepared the candidates that Step 3 must now audit. The mission
+question is still open because the three promoted notions may yet survive,
+split, or fail under robustness analysis. Stopping now would confuse
+intermediate branch progress with a finished mission result.
+
+## Chain Assessment
+
+The chain remains `active`.
+
+The next logical move is:
+**Run a tiered robustness audit instead of a single invariance veto.**
+
+That next step should stay tightly scoped to the promoted Step-2 candidates. It
+should classify transformations into exact symmetries, canonicalization
+choices, and substantive modeling changes; test each candidate against those
+classes; and return a robustness matrix plus a Step-4 readiness verdict.
