# Decision Memo - exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit / decision-013

## Decision

`proceed`

## Mission-Control Verdict

This is a bootstrap launch decision for the new chain selected in planning run
`run-003`. The prior controller decision,
`decision-012`,
already invalidated the old
`F_SS(1/12)`
dynamic-audit branch after
`step-008`
showed that the frozen record earned only a classwise exact-closure picture and
the witness-local verdict
`exact non-isolability / arbitrary-truncation requirement`,
not one finite exact closed subsystem that later dynamics could inherit.

The current question is therefore not whether that old branch should continue.
It should not. The question is whether the replanned branch now frozen in
`CHAIN.md`
is the right next mission move. It is. The new chain is aimed exactly at the
missing object exposed by
`step-008`:
one explicit audited realization protocol with declared freedoms, a precise
finite-closure convention, same-currency provenance for any promoted exact data,
and explicit scope control before any obstruction or loophole rhetoric.

That makes `proceed` the conservative choice. The branch does not pretend that
support bookkeeping already proves no finite closure, and it does not reuse the
invalidated dynamic-audit chain under a new name. Instead it inserts the exact
realization-and-authority gate that the repository lacked. If that gate fails,
the chain itself already instructs the branch to stop with a source-basis or
no-canonical-finite-reduction memo. If it succeeds, later steps can perform a
recursive closure audit and cancellation analysis on an honest object.

## Why `replan` Is Wrong

Mission control already replanned in
`decision-012`,
and planning run
`run-003`
returned a clear single winner. The winning chain was promoted into
`winning-chain.md`
and mirrored into the active
`CHAIN.md`.
Nothing in the bootstrap record weakens that selection. Replanning again before
running Chain Step 1 would amount to rejecting a fresh branch without testing
its entry gate.

## Why `terminate` Is Wrong

The mission-level question is still open. The repository still lacks:

- a scoped no-near-closed-circuit theorem on an audited exact realization;
- a robust loophole family or near-circuit construction that kills the
  obstruction idea; or
- a final mission-level definition failure covering the surviving one-bridge
  route.

The new chain is designed to decide whether one of those endpoints can actually
be earned. So the mission should continue.

## Next Step

Launch
`step-009`
as logical Chain Step 1:

`Freeze The Inherited Ledger, Provenance Burden, Remaining Freedoms, And Claim Scope`

That step should freeze one audited realization-and-provenance memo and decide,
before any recursive closure work, exactly what data are inherited, what
freedoms remain open, what same-currency source basis authorizes later exact
claims, and how far any later theorem statement is allowed to range.

